    <fr:title text="Decidability of regular expression matching › "><fr:link href="jms-018E.xml" title="Decidability of regular expression matching" addr="jms-018E" type="local">Decidability of <fr:link href="jms-017C.xml" title="Regular expression matching" addr="jms-017C" type="local">regular expression matching</fr:link></fr:link> › </fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>The idea of the proof is to find a <fr:link href="jms-017L.xml" title="Deterministic finite automaton" addr="jms-017L" type="local">DFA</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> satisfying <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (M\right )\mathclose {}}=\mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (R\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>; so for this we need only <fr:link href="jms-018A.xml" title="All regular languages are automatical" addr="jms-018A" type="local">Corollary <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-018A" /></fr:link> rather than the full <fr:link href="jms-018B.xml" title="Kleene’s theorem" addr="jms-018B" type="local">Kleene’s theorem</fr:link>. Then our algorithm is to feed the given string <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u]]></fr:tex> through <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> and check whether the final state is accepting or not.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter>
